{"title_page": "George Lambert, 1st Viscount Lambert", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Viscount Lambert\n| honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n| image = 1921 George Lambert.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Lambert in 1921\n| constituency_MP = [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]]\n| parliament = United Kingdom\n| term_start = 1891\n| term_end = 1924\n| predecessor = [[Newton Wallop]]\n| successor = [[Cedric Drewe]]\n| constituency_MP2 = South Molton\n| parliament2 = United Kingdom\n| term_start2 = 1929\n| term_end2 = 1945\n| predecessor2 = Cedric Drewe\n| successor2 = [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1866|6|25}}\n| birth_place = [[South Tawton]], [[Devon]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1958|2|17|1866|6|25}}\n| death_place = [[Spreyton]], Devon, England\n| party = {{unbulleted list| [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] (1891-1931)| [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|National Liberal]] (1931-1958)}}\n| children = George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert\n}}\n'''George Lambert, 1st Viscount Lambert''', [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] (25 June 1866 \u2013 17 February 1958) was a long-serving [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP).\n\n==Birth and education==\n[[File:George Lambert.jpg|thumb|left|George Lambert c1895]]\n[[File:1910 George Lambert MP.jpg|thumb|left|George Lambert c1910]]\nLambert was born in [[South Tawton]] in Devon, on 25 June 1866, the son of George Lambert Gorwyn and his wife, Grace Howard.\n\nGeorge Lambert Gorwyn (1818-1885), who is remembered today as a quarrelsome and much disliked man, had inherited farms in [[Spreyton]] and [[Drewsteignton]]. He dropped the surname Gorwyn in the 1870s, becoming known merely as George Lambert. His wife, Grace Howard, was the daughter of a farm labourer from South Tawton, who had been his housekeeper. They married in 1866.<ref name=lhs>{{cite web |url=http://lambert-gorwyn.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/Table-4-chart.pdf|title=TABLE 4: the George Lamberts of Spreyton|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nLambert was educated at Spreyton School and [[North Tawton]] Grammar School. He left school after his father's death in 1885, and commenced farming.<ref>''North Exeter and Plymouth Gazette'' (Friday, 15 May 1936), p. 10. ''Dod's Parliamentary Companion, 1907'', p. 288.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLambert served as a [[County Councillor]] for Devonshire, 1889\u20131912, and as a County Alderman, 1912\u20131952.<ref>''Debrett's Peerage'' (1963), p. 711.</ref>\n\nHe was first elected as [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] MP for [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]] at [[1891 South Molton by-election|a by-election]] in 1891.  He was [[Civil Lord of the Admiralty (Royal Navy)|Civil Lord of the Admiralty]], 1905\u20131915, \"a post for which he had no obvious qualifications. 'A farmer sent to sea' was a jibe frequently heard in those days\" (''The Times'').<ref>''The Times'' (London, England) (Tuesday, 18 Feb 1958, p. 11).</ref>  \nHe lost his seat at the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 General Election]] to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Cedric Drewe]], but regained it at the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]] general election.  Although he began his parliamentary career as a Liberal, in 1931 Lambert had become a [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|National Liberal]] supporting the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], following a long period criticising [[David Lloyd George]] and opposition to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\nLambert was made a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Councillor]] in 1912, and later the same year he was appointed to the [[Royal Commission on Fuel and Engines]].<ref>''The Times'', ''loc. cit''.</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28632 |date=2 August 1912 |page=5721}}</ref> He was created [[Viscount Lambert]] when he stepped down as an MP in July 1945, after 48 years, 348 days in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], the fifth longest-serving MP of the 20th century.\n\nHis eldest son, the Hon. [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert|George Lambert]], followed him as MP for South Molton, later [[Torrington (UK Parliament constituency)|Torrington]], at the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]], and succeeded him as Viscount Lambert in 1958.\n\n==Personal life==\nLambert was married on 30 August 1904 to Barbara Stavers, the daughter of George Stavers, a ship-owner of Morpeth, by whom he had two daughters and two sons.<ref>''Dod's Peerage'' (1954), p. 138. ''The Times'', ''loc. cit''.</ref>\n\nHe died, aged 91 years, at his home, \"''Coffins''\" in Spreyton on 17 February 1958.\n\nLambert \"was a good shot, and was also fond of a round of golf.\"<ref>''The Times'', ''loc. cit''.</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Lambert Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure a Chevron Or fretty of the first between in chief two Garbs and in base a Fleece of the second\n|crest = Issuant from a Mount Vert an Apple Tree fructed proper\n|supporters = On either side a Cornish Chough proper collared Or\n|motto = The Good Earth Provides <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lambert1945.htm</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=February 2012}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-george-lambert | George Lambert }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]]\n | years  = [[1891 South Molton by-election|1891]]\u2013[[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\n | before = [[Newton Wallop]]\n | after  = [[Cedric Drewe]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]]\n | years  = [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]]\u2013[[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]\n | before = [[Cedric Drewe]]\n | after  = [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert|George Lambert (2nd)]]\n}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Viscount Lambert]]\n | years = 1945\u20131958\n}}\n{{s-aft |after = [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert|George Lambert]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lambert, George}}\n[[Category:1866 births|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Lords of the Admiralty]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (UK, 1931) politicians]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Norway Debate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Viscount Lambert\n| honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n| image = 1921 George Lambert.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Lambert in 1921\n| constituency_MP = [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]]\n| parliament = United Kingdom\n| term_start = 1891\n| term_end = 1924\n| predecessor = [[Newton Wallop]]\n| successor = [[Cedric Drewe]]\n| constituency_MP2 = South Molton\n| parliament2 = United Kingdom\n| term_start2 = 1929\n| term_end2 = 1945\n| predecessor2 = Cedric Drewe\n| successor2 = [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1866|6|25}}\n| birth_place = [[South Tawton]], [[Devon]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1958|2|17|1866|6|25}}\n| death_place = [[Spreyton]], Devon, England\n| party = {{unbulleted list| [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] (1891-1931)| [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|National Liberal]] (1931-1958)}}\n| children = George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert\n}}\n'''George Lambert, 1st Viscount Lambert''', [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] (25 June 1866 \u2013 17 February 1958) was a long-serving [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Member of Parliament]] (MP).\n\n==Birth and education==\n[[File:George Lambert.jpg|thumb|left|George Lambert c1895]]\n[[File:1910 George Lambert MP.jpg|thumb|left|George Lambert c1910]]\nLambert was born in [[South Tawton]] in Devon, on 25 June 1866, the son of George Lambert Gorwyn and his wife, Grace Howard.\n\nGeorge Lambert Gorwyn (1818-1885), who is remembered today as a quarrelsome and much disliked man, had inherited farms in [[Spreyton]] and [[Drewsteignton]]. He dropped the surname Gorwyn in the 1870s, becoming known merely as George Lambert. His wife, Grace Howard, was the daughter of a farm labourer from South Tawton, who had been his housekeeper. They married in 1866.<ref name=lhs>{{cite web |url=http://lambert-gorwyn.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/Table-4-chart.pdf|title=TABLE 4: the George Lamberts of Spreyton|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nLambert was educated at Spreyton School and [[North Tawton]] Grammar School. He left school after his father's death in 1885, and commenced farming.<ref>''North Exeter and Plymouth Gazette'' (Friday, 15 May 1936), p. 10. ''Dod's Parliamentary Companion, 1907'', p. 288.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLambert served as a [[County Councillor]] for Devonshire, 1889-1912, and as a County Alderman, 1912-1952.<ref>''Debrett's Peerage'' (1963), p. 711.</ref>\n\nHe was first elected as [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] MP for [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]] at [[1891 South Molton by-election|a by-election]] in 1891.  He was [[Civil Lord of the Admiralty (Royal Navy)|Civil Lord of the Admiralty]], 1905-1915, \"a post for which he had no obvious qualifications. 'A farmer sent to sea' was a jibe frequently heard in those days\" (''The Times'').<ref>''The Times'' (London, England) (Tuesday, 18 Feb 1958, p. 11).</ref>  \nHe lost his seat at the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 General Election]] to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Cedric Drewe]], but regained it at the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]] general election.  Although he began his parliamentary career as a Liberal, in 1931 Lambert had become a [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|National Liberal]] supporting the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], following a long period criticising [[David Lloyd George]] and opposition to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\nLambert was made a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Councillor]] in 1912, and later the same year he was appointed to the [[Royal Commission on Fuel and Engines]].<ref>''The Times'', ''loc. cit''.</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28632 |date=2 August 1912 |page=5721}}</ref> He was created [[Viscount Lambert]] when he stepped down as an MP in July 1945, after 48 years, 348 days in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], the fifth longest-serving MP of the 20th century.\n\nHis eldest son, the Hon. [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert|George Lambert]], followed him as MP for South Molton, later [[Torrington (UK Parliament constituency)|Torrington]], at the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]], and succeeded him as Viscount Lambert in 1958.\n\n==Personal life==\nLambert was married on 30 August 1904 to Barbara Stavers, the daughter of George Stavers, a ship-owner of Morpeth, by whom he had two daughters and two sons.<ref>''Dod's Peerage'' (1954), p. 138. ''The Times'', ''loc. cit''.</ref>\n\nHe died, aged 91 years, at his home, \"''Coffins''\" in Spreyton on 17 February 1958.\n\nLambert \"was a good shot, and was also fond of a round of golf.\"<ref>''The Times'', ''loc. cit''.</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Lambert Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure a Chevron Or fretty of the first between in chief two Garbs and in base a Fleece of the second\n|crest = Issuant from a Mount Vert an Apple Tree fructed proper\n|supporters = On either side a Cornish Chough proper collared Or\n|motto = The Good Earth Provides <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lambert1945.htm</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=February 2012}}\n*{{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-george-lambert | George Lambert }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]]\n | years  = [[1891 South Molton by-election|1891]]\u2013[[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\n | before = [[Newton Wallop]]\n | after  = [[Cedric Drewe]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[South Molton (UK Parliament constituency)|South Molton]]\n | years  = [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]]\u2013[[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]\n | before = [[Cedric Drewe]]\n | after  = [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert|George Lambert (2nd)]]\n}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Viscount Lambert]]\n | years = 1945\u20131958\n}}\n{{s-aft |after = [[George Lambert, 2nd Viscount Lambert|George Lambert]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lambert, George}}\n[[Category:1866 births|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Lambert, George Lambert, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1918\u20131922]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Lords of the Admiralty]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (UK, 1931) politicians]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Norway Debate]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1889-1912 \u2192 1889\u20131912 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Lambert,_1st_Viscount_Lambert"}
{"title_page": "Arthur Frederick Jeffreys", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Arthur Frederick Jeffreys\n| image       = Arthur Frederick Jeffreys (Justice of the peace).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1848|4|7}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1906|2|14|1848|4|7}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = \n}}\n'''Arthur Frederick Jeffreys''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (7 April 1848 \u2013 14 February 1906), of Burkham House in [[Hampshire]], was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\nJeffreys was the son of [[Arthur Jeffreys]], member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Council]], who had emigrated to [[Australia]] in 1839. During his youth he was a successful cricketer with [[Hampshire county cricket teams|Hampshire]] and [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]].<ref name=\"CI\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/6016.html |title=Arthur Frederick Jeffreys |accessdate=1 January 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref><ref name=\"CA\">{{Cite web |url-access=subscription  |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5927/5927.html |title=Arthur Frederick Jeffreys |accessdate=1 January 2017 |work=Cricket Archive}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Christ Church, Oxford]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]]. He studied law at the [[Inner Temple]] and was called to the bar in 1872.  He served as a justice of the peace for [[Hampshire]].<ref name=\"matb\" />\n\nHe was elected to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Basingstoke]] in 1887, a seat he held until his death. He was sworn a member of the Imperial [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] on 11 August 1902,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27464 |date=12 August 1902 |page=5174 }}</ref> following an announcement of the King's intention to make this appointment in the [[1902 Coronation Honours]] list published in June that year.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Coronation Honours |day_of_week=Thursday |date=26 June 1902 |page_number=5 |issue=36804| }}</ref> He served briefly under [[Arthur Balfour]] as [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Local Government Board]] from June to December 1905.\n\nJeffreys died in February 1906, aged 57. In 1877 he married Amy Fenwick, and their son [[George Jeffreys, 1st Baron Jeffreys (British Army officer)|George]] became a prominent military commander and was elevated to the peerage as [[Baron Jeffreys]] in 1952.<ref name=\"matb\" /><ref name=\"cra\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"matb\">{{cite Men-at-the-Bar|name=Jeffreys, Arthur Frederick|page=241}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"cra\">{{cite web|title=Jeffreys, Baron (UK 1952) |work=Cracroft's Peerage |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1014.htm |accessdate=2011-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331190522/http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1014.htm |archivedate=31 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990.\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926222637/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/members.nsf/0/80dad3cb6a6d6486ca256f31001799cd?OpenDocument Parliament of New South Wales - Information on father]\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-arthur-jeffreys | Arthur Jeffreys }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Basingstoke]] | years = 1887 \u2013 [[1906 Basingstoke by-election|1906]] | before = [[George Sclater-Booth, 1st Baron Basing|George Sclater-Booth]] | after = [[Arthur Salter (judge)|Arthur Clavell Salter]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Local Government Board]] | years = 1905 | before = Sir [[Sir John Lawson, 1st Baronet of Knavesmire|John Grant Lawson]] | after = [[Walter Runciman, 1st Viscount Runciman of Doxford|Walter Runciman]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeffreys, Arthur Frederick}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Hampshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:New South Wales cricketers]]\n[[Category:British sportsperson-politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Arthur Frederick Jeffreys\n| image       = Arthur Frederick Jeffreys (Justice of the peace).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1848|4|7}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1906|2|14|1848|4|7}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = \n}}\n'''Arthur Frederick Jeffreys''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (7 April 1848 \u2013 14 February 1906), of Burkham House in [[Hampshire]], was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician.\n\nJeffreys was the son of [[Arthur Jeffreys]], member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Council]], who had emigrated to [[Australia]] in 1839. During his youth he was a successful cricketer with [[Hampshire county cricket teams|Hampshire]] and [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]].<ref name=\"CI\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/6016.html |title=Arthur Frederick Jeffreys |accessdate=1 January 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref><ref name=\"CA\">{{Cite web |url-access=subscription  |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5927/5927.html |title=Arthur Frederick Jeffreys |accessdate=1 January 2017 |work=Cricket Archive}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from [[Christ Church, Oxford]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]]. He studied law at the [[Inner Temple]] and was called to the bar in 1872.  He served as a justice of the peace for [[Hampshire]].<ref name=\"matb\" />\n\nHe was elected to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Basingstoke]] in 1887, a seat he held until his death. He was sworn a member of the Imperial [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] on 11 August 1902,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=27464 |date=12 August 1902 |page=5174 }}</ref> following an announcement of the King\u2032s intention to make this appointment in the [[1902 Coronation Honours]] list published in June that year.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Coronation Honours |day_of_week=Thursday |date=26 June 1902 |page_number=5 |issue=36804| }}</ref> He served briefly under [[Arthur Balfour]] as [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Local Government Board]] from June to December 1905.\n\nJeffreys died in February 1906, aged 57. In 1877 he married Amy Fenwick, and their son [[George Jeffreys, 1st Baron Jeffreys (British Army officer)|George]] became a prominent military commander and was elevated to the peerage as [[Baron Jeffreys]] in 1952.<ref name=\"matb\" /><ref name=\"cra\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"matb\">{{cite Men-at-the-Bar|name=Jeffreys, Arthur Frederick|page=241}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"cra\">{{cite web|title=Jeffreys, Baron (UK 1952) |work=Cracroft's Peerage |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1014.htm |accessdate=2011-03-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331190522/http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1014.htm |archivedate=31 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990.\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926222637/http://www.parliament.nsw.gov.au/prod/parlment/members.nsf/0/80dad3cb6a6d6486ca256f31001799cd?OpenDocument Parliament of New South Wales - Information on father]\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-arthur-jeffreys | Arthur Jeffreys }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Basingstoke]] | years = 1887 \u2013 [[1906 Basingstoke by-election|1906]] | before = [[George Sclater-Booth, 1st Baron Basing|George Sclater-Booth]] | after = [[Arthur Salter (judge)|Arthur Clavell Salter]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Local Government Board]] | years = 1905 | before = Sir [[Sir John Lawson, 1st Baronet of Knavesmire|John Grant Lawson]] | after = [[Walter Runciman, 1st Viscount Runciman of Doxford|Walter Runciman]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeffreys, Arthur Frederick}}\n[[Category:1848 births]]\n[[Category:1906 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1892\u20131895]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Hampshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:New South Wales cricketers]]\n[[Category:British sportsperson-politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2032s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Frederick_Jeffreys"}
{"title_page": "Henry Harrison (Irish politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\nCaptain '''Henry Harrison''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|MC*|MP}} (17 December 1867 \u2013 20 February 1954) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] politician. He served as [[Member of Parliament|MP]] in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] and as member of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] represented [[Mid Tipperary (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Tipperary]] from 1890 to 1892. He later served as a [[Royal Irish Regiment (1684\u20131922)|Royal Irish Regiment]] officer with the [[Kitchener's Army|New British Army]] in [[World War I]], was an extensive writer, and proponent of improved relations between the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].\n\n==Biography==\nA [[Protestant Nationalist|Protestant nationalist]], Harrison was the son of Henry Harrison of [[Holywood]] and [[Ardkeen (civil parish)|Ardkeen]], [[Co. Down]] and of Letitia Tennent. She was the daughter of [[Robert James Tennent]], who had been [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] MP for [[Belfast (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast]] from 1847 to 1852.  Later, when widowed, she married the author Hartley Withers.\n\nHarrison went to [[Westminster School]] and then to [[Balliol College]], [[Oxford University|Oxford]]. While there he developed an admiration for [[Charles Stewart Parnell]] and became secretary of the Oxford University [[Home Rule League|Home Rule Group]]. At this time, the [[Land War]] was in progress and in 1889 Harrison went to Ireland to visit the scene of the evictions in [[Gweedore]], [[Co. Donegal]]. He became involved in physical confrontations with the [[Royal Irish Constabulary]] and as a result became a Nationalist celebrity overnight. The following May, Parnell offered the vacant parliamentary seat of Mid-Tipperary to Harrison, who left Oxford, still aged only 22, to take it up, unopposed.\n\nOnly six months later, following the divorce case involving [[Katharine O'Shea]], the Irish Parliamentary Party split over Parnell's leadership. Harrison strongly supported Parnell, acted as his bodyguard and aide-de-camp, and after Parnell's death devoted himself to the service of his widow Katharine. From her he heard a completely different version of the events surrounding the divorce case from that which had appeared in the press, and this was to form the seed of his later books.\n\nAt the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1892]], Harrison did not defend Mid-Tipperary. He stood at [[West Limerick (UK Parliament constituency)|West Limerick]] as a [[Parnellite]] instead, but came nowhere near winning the seat. In [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]], he stood at [[North Sligo (UK Parliament constituency)|North Sligo]], polling better but again far short of winning.<ref>''The Times'', Obituary, 22 February 1954, states that Harrison did not seek to stand for Parliament again after the end of his initial term in 1892.  This is a mistake as ''The Times'' itself reported his candidacies in 1892 and 1895.</ref> In 1895 Harrison married Maie Byrne, an American, with whom he had a son. He came to prominence briefly again in 1903 when, in spite of his lack of legal training, he successfully conducted his own case in a court action all the way to the [[British House of Lords|House of Lords]].\n\nOtherwise, however, he disappeared from public view until his war service with the [[Royal Irish Regiment (1684-1922)|Royal Irish Regiment]] when he served on the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]] with distinction in the [[Kitchener's Army|New British Army]] formed for the [[First World War]], reaching the rank of Captain and being awarded the [[Military Cross|MC]]. He organised patrols in \"[[No man's land|No Man's Land]]\" so successfully that he was appointed special patrol officer to the [[16th (Irish) Division]]. He was invalided out and became a recruiting officer in Ireland. He was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] in the [[1919 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31114 |supp=y |page=455|date= 8 January 1919}}</ref>\n\nHe then made a return to Irish politics, working with [[Horace Plunkett|Sir Horace Plunkett]] as Secretary of the [[Irish Dominion League]], an organisation campaigning for [[dominion status]] for Ireland within the [[British Empire]]. Harrison was a lifelong opponent of [[Partition of Ireland|Irish partition]]. He was Irish correspondent of ''The Economist'' from 1922 to 1927 and owner-editor of ''Irish Truth'' from 1924 to 1927.\n\nHarrison's two books defending Parnell were published in 1931 and 1938. They have had a major impact on Irish historiography, leading to a more favourable view of Parnell's role in the O\u2019Shea affair. [[F. S. L. Lyons]]<ref>(1977, p.324)</ref> commented that he \"did more than anyone else to uncover what seems to have been the true facts\" about the Parnell-O'Shea liaison. The second book, ''Parnell, Joseph Chamberlain and Mr Garvin'', was written in response to [[James Louis Garvin|J. L. Garvin]]'s biography of [[Joseph Chamberlain]], which had ignored Harrison's first book, ''Parnell Vindicated:  The Lifting of the Veil''.  Later, Harrison successfully repulsed an attempt in the official history of ''The Times'' to rehabilitate that newspaper's role in using forged letters to attack Parnell in the later 1880s. In 1952 he forced ''The Times'' to publish a four-page correction written by him as an appendix to the fourth volume of the history.\n\nDuring the difficult years of the [[Anglo-Irish Trade War]] over the land purchase annuities, [[John A. Costello#Declaration of the republic|declaration of the Republic]], [[Irish neutrality during World War II]], and departure from the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]], Harrison worked to promote good relations between Britain and Ireland. He published various books and pamphlets on the issues in dispute and wrote numerous letters to ''The Times''. He also founded, with General Sir [[Hubert Gough]], the [[Commonwealth Irish Association]] in 1942. By the time of his death, he was the last survivor of the Irish Parliamentary Party led by Parnell, and as a member of the pre-1918 Irish Parliamentary Party, he seems to have been outlived only by [[John Patrick Hayden]], who died a few months after him in 1954 and by [[Patrick Whitty]] and [[John Lymbrick Esmonde]] who were only MPs for a very short time during the First World War.\nHe is buried in [[Holywood]], [[Co Down]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Parnell Vindicated:  the lifting of the veil'', London, Constable, 1931\n* ''The Strange Case of the Irish Land Purchase Annuities'', Dublin, M. H. Gill, 1932\n* ''Ireland and the British Empire, 1937:  Conflict or Collaboration?:  A study of Anglo-Irish differences from an international standpoint'', London, Robert Hale & Co., 1937\n* ''Parnell, Joseph Chamberlain and Mr Garvin'', London, Robert Hale, 1938\n* ''Ulster and the British Empire 1939'', London, Robert Hale, 1939\n* ''The Partition of Ireland:  How Britain is responsible'', London, Robert Hale, 1939\n* ''The Neutrality of Ireland:  Why it was inevitable'', London, Robert Hale Ltd, 1942\n* ''Parnell, Joseph Chamberlain and \u201cThe Times\u201d:  A Documentary Record:  tempora mutantur'', Belfast, Irish News;  Dublin, Brown & Nolan, 1953\n\n==References==\n* ''Irish Independent'', 20 February 1954\n* F. S. L. Lyons, ''Charles Stewart Parnell'', London, Collins, 1977\n* Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, ''Henry Harrison'' by F. S. L. Lyons, rev. Mark Pottle\n* ''The Times'' (London), 22 February 1954\n* Brian M. Walker (ed.), ''Parliamentary Election Results in Ireland, 1801-1922'', Dublin, Royal Irish Academy, 1978\n* ''Who Was Who, 1951-1960''\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-henry-harrison | Henry Harrison }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Thomas Mayne (politician)|Thomas Mayne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mid Tipperary (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Tipperary]] \n       |years  = [[1890 Mid Tipperary by-election|1890]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[John McCarthy (Irish politician)|John McCarthy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Babies of the House}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrison, Henry}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:People from County Down]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:Protestant Irish nationalists]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Royal Irish Regiment (1684\u20131922) officers]]\n[[Category:Irish people of World War I]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Tipperary constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Parnellite MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1886\u20131892]]\n[[Category:Male non-fiction writers from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Military Cross]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Irish Protestants]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\nCaptain '''Henry Harrison''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|MC*|MP}} (17 December 1867 \u2013 20 February 1954) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] politician. He served as [[Member of Parliament|MP]] in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] and as member of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] represented [[Mid Tipperary (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Tipperary]] from 1890 to 1892. He later served as a [[Royal Irish Regiment (1684\u20131922)|Royal Irish Regiment]] officer with the [[Kitchener's Army|New British Army]] in [[World War I]], was an extensive writer, and proponent of improved relations between the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].\n\n==Biography==\nA [[Protestant Nationalist|Protestant nationalist]], Harrison was the son of Henry Harrison of [[Holywood]] and [[Ardkeen (civil parish)|Ardkeen]], [[Co. Down]] and of Letitia Tennent. She was the daughter of [[Robert James Tennent]], who had been [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] MP for [[Belfast (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast]] from 1847 to 1852.  Later, when widowed, she married the author Hartley Withers.\n\nHarrison went to [[Westminster School]] and then to [[Balliol College]], [[Oxford University|Oxford]]. While there he developed an admiration for [[Charles Stewart Parnell]] and became secretary of the Oxford University [[Home Rule League|Home Rule Group]]. At this time, the [[Land War]] was in progress and in 1889 Harrison went to Ireland to visit the scene of the evictions in [[Gweedore]], [[Co. Donegal]]. He became involved in physical confrontations with the [[Royal Irish Constabulary]] and as a result became a Nationalist celebrity overnight. The following May, Parnell offered the vacant parliamentary seat of Mid-Tipperary to Harrison, who left Oxford, still aged only 22, to take it up, unopposed.\n\nOnly six months later, following the divorce case involving [[Katharine O'Shea]], the Irish Parliamentary Party split over Parnell\u2019s leadership. Harrison strongly supported Parnell, acted as his bodyguard and aide-de-camp, and after Parnell\u2019s death devoted himself to the service of his widow Katharine. From her he heard a completely different version of the events surrounding the divorce case from that which had appeared in the press, and this was to form the seed of his later books.\n\nAt the [[1892 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1892]], Harrison did not defend Mid-Tipperary. He stood at [[West Limerick (UK Parliament constituency)|West Limerick]] as a [[Parnellite]] instead, but came nowhere near winning the seat. In [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895 general election]], he stood at [[North Sligo (UK Parliament constituency)|North Sligo]], polling better but again far short of winning.<ref>''The Times'', Obituary, 22 February 1954, states that Harrison did not seek to stand for Parliament again after the end of his initial term in 1892.  This is a mistake as ''The Times'' itself reported his candidacies in 1892 and 1895.</ref> In 1895 Harrison married Maie Byrne, an American, with whom he had a son. He came to prominence briefly again in 1903 when, in spite of his lack of legal training, he successfully conducted his own case in a court action all the way to the [[British House of Lords|House of Lords]].\n\nOtherwise, however, he disappeared from public view until his war service with the [[Royal Irish Regiment (1684-1922)|Royal Irish Regiment]] when he served on the [[Western Front (WWI)|Western Front]] with distinction in the [[Kitchener's Army|New British Army]] formed for the [[First World War]], reaching the rank of Captain and being awarded the [[Military Cross|MC]]. He organised patrols in \"[[No man's land|No Man's Land]]\" so successfully that he was appointed special patrol officer to the [[16th (Irish) Division]]. He was invalided out and became a recruiting officer in Ireland. He was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] in the [[1919 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31114 |supp=y |page=455|date= 8 January 1919}}</ref>\n\nHe then made a return to Irish politics, working with [[Horace Plunkett|Sir Horace Plunkett]] as Secretary of the [[Irish Dominion League]], an organisation campaigning for [[dominion status]] for Ireland within the [[British Empire]]. Harrison was a lifelong opponent of [[Partition of Ireland|Irish partition]]. He was Irish correspondent of ''The Economist'' from 1922 to 1927 and owner-editor of ''Irish Truth'' from 1924 to 1927.\n\nHarrison\u2019s two books defending Parnell were published in 1931 and 1938. They have had a major impact on Irish historiography, leading to a more favourable view of Parnell\u2019s role in the O\u2019Shea affair. [[F. S. L. Lyons]]<ref>(1977, p.324)</ref> commented that he \"did more than anyone else to uncover what seems to have been the true facts\" about the Parnell-O'Shea liaison. The second book, ''Parnell, Joseph Chamberlain and Mr Garvin'', was written in response to [[James Louis Garvin|J. L. Garvin]]'s biography of [[Joseph Chamberlain]], which had ignored Harrison\u2019s first book, ''Parnell Vindicated:  The Lifting of the Veil''.  Later, Harrison successfully repulsed an attempt in the official history of ''The Times'' to rehabilitate that newspaper\u2019s role in using forged letters to attack Parnell in the later 1880s. In 1952 he forced ''The Times'' to publish a four-page correction written by him as an appendix to the fourth volume of the history.\n\nDuring the difficult years of the [[Anglo-Irish Trade War]] over the land purchase annuities, [[John A. Costello#Declaration of the republic|declaration of the Republic]], [[Irish neutrality during World War II]], and departure from the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]], Harrison worked to promote good relations between Britain and Ireland. He published various books and pamphlets on the issues in dispute and wrote numerous letters to ''The Times''. He also founded, with General Sir [[Hubert Gough]], the [[Commonwealth Irish Association]] in 1942. By the time of his death, he was the last survivor of the Irish Parliamentary Party led by Parnell, and as a member of the pre-1918 Irish Parliamentary Party, he seems to have been outlived only by [[John Patrick Hayden]], who died a few months after him in 1954 and by [[Patrick Whitty]] and [[John Lymbrick Esmonde]] who were only MPs for a very short time during the First World War.\nHe is buried in [[Holywood]], [[Co Down]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''Parnell Vindicated:  the lifting of the veil'', London, Constable, 1931\n* ''The Strange Case of the Irish Land Purchase Annuities'', Dublin, M. H. Gill, 1932\n* ''Ireland and the British Empire, 1937:  Conflict or Collaboration?:  A study of Anglo-Irish differences from an international standpoint'', London, Robert Hale & Co., 1937\n* ''Parnell, Joseph Chamberlain and Mr Garvin'', London, Robert Hale, 1938\n* ''Ulster and the British Empire 1939'', London, Robert Hale, 1939\n* ''The Partition of Ireland:  How Britain is responsible'', London, Robert Hale, 1939\n* ''The Neutrality of Ireland:  Why it was inevitable'', London, Robert Hale Ltd, 1942\n* ''Parnell, Joseph Chamberlain and \u201cThe Times\u201d:  A Documentary Record:  tempora mutantur'', Belfast, Irish News;  Dublin, Brown & Nolan, 1953\n\n==References==\n* ''Irish Independent'', 20 February 1954\n* F. S. L. Lyons, ''Charles Stewart Parnell'', London, Collins, 1977\n* Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, ''Henry Harrison'' by F. S. L. Lyons, rev. Mark Pottle\n* ''The Times'' (London), 22 February 1954\n* Brian M. Walker (ed.), ''Parliamentary Election Results in Ireland, 1801-1922'', Dublin, Royal Irish Academy, 1978\n* ''Who Was Who, 1951-1960''\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-henry-harrison | Henry Harrison }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Thomas Mayne (politician)|Thomas Mayne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Mid Tipperary (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Tipperary]] \n       |years  = [[1890 Mid Tipperary by-election|1890]] \u2013 [[1892 United Kingdom general election|1892]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[John McCarthy (Irish politician)|John McCarthy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Babies of the House}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harrison, Henry}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:People from County Down]]\n[[Category:People educated at Westminster School, London]]\n[[Category:Protestant Irish nationalists]]\n[[