{"title_page": "Michael Joseph Flavin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:Michael Joseph Flavin 1901.jpg|thumb|Michael Joseph Flavin in 1901]]\n'''Michael Joseph Flavin''' (1866<ref>The Times, 4 May 1944, and Who Was Who, both give the birth date as 1861, while The Times, 7 December 1910, Stenton & Lees (1978) and Hansard 1803-2005 online give it as 1866. If the information given by The Times, 7 December 1910 and by ''Who Was Who'' that Flavin attended St Michael's College, Listowel, is correct, then Flavin must have been born in 1866 as this secondary school was not founded until 1879.</ref>  \u2013 3 May 1944) was an [[Irish Nationalist]] Member of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] for [[North Kerry (UK Parliament constituency)|North Kerry]], 1896\u20131918.\n \nFlavin was born at Ballyduff, near [[Listowel]].<ref>Stenton & Lees (1978)</ref> He was the son of James Flavin and Joan<ref>Who Was Who</ref> or Johanna<ref>Stenton & Lees (1978)</ref> Mangan. He was educated at National schools, at [[St. Michael's College, Listowel]] (a Catholic diocesan secondary school), and privately. He was a merchant in Listowel and [[Tralee]], President of the Listowel [[Young Ireland]] Society<ref>Stenton & Lees (1978)</ref> and was a member of Kerry County Council and of the committee governing the County Infirmary, Tralee, the County Fever Hospital, Tralee and the County Mental Hospital, Killarney.  He married Mary Elizabeth Fitzgerald and they had three sons and two daughters.<ref>The Times, 7 December 1910; ''Who Was Who, 1941-1950''</ref>\n\nIn April 1896 he was returned unopposed as Anti-Parnellite Nationalist M.P. for North Kerry after the resignation of [[Thomas Sexton (Irish politician)|Thomas Sexton]].  Following the reunification of the Irish Parliamentary Party, he held the seat unopposed in 1900 and 1906.  In January 1910 he faced a challenge from an independent Nationalist, Thomas Stack, but was easily returned by 2,637 votes to 885. In December 1910 he was again returned unopposed.  He did not stand in the general election of 1918.<ref>Walker (1978)</ref>\n \nHe died at Tralee on 3 May 1944.<ref>The Times, 4 May 1944</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|title=Parliamentary Election Results in Ireland, 1801-1922|editor=Brian M. Walker|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|location=Dublin|year=1978}}\n*{{cite book|title=Who Was Who, 1941-1950|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=London|year=2012}}\n*{{cite book|title=Who\u2019s Who of British Members of Parliament, Vol.2 1886-1918|author=Michael Stenton and Stephen Lees|publisher=Harvester Press|location=Sussex|year=1978}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{hansard-contribs | mr-michael-flavin | Michael Flavin }}\n* {{cite TIWW |article= Flavin, Michael Joseph|page=84 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Stack (politician)|John Stack]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[North Kerry (UK Parliament constituency)|North Kerry]]\n | years = [[1896 North Kerry by-election|1896]] &ndash; [[1918 Irish general election|1918]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[James Crowley (Irish politician)|James Crowley]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flavin, Michael Joseph}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Kerry constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:People from Listowel]]\n[[Category:People from Tralee]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in County Kerry]]\n[[Category:Anti-Parnellite MPs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:Michael Joseph Flavin 1901.jpg|thumb|Michael Joseph Flavin in 1901]]\n'''Michael Joseph Flavin''' (1866<ref>The Times, 4 May 1944, and Who Was Who, both give the birth date as 1861, while The Times, 7 December 1910, Stenton & Lees (1978) and Hansard 1803-2005 online give it as 1866. If the information given by The Times, 7 December 1910 and by ''Who Was Who'' that Flavin attended St Michael's College, Listowel, is correct, then Flavin must have been born in 1866 as this secondary school was not founded until 1879.</ref>  \u2013 3 May 1944) was an [[Irish Nationalist]] Member of [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] for [[North Kerry (UK Parliament constituency)|North Kerry]], 1896-1918.\n \nFlavin was born at Ballyduff, near [[Listowel]].<ref>Stenton & Lees (1978)</ref> He was the son of James Flavin and Joan<ref>Who Was Who</ref> or Johanna<ref>Stenton & Lees (1978)</ref> Mangan. He was educated at National schools, at [[St. Michael's College, Listowel]] (a Catholic diocesan secondary school), and privately. He was a merchant in Listowel and [[Tralee]], President of the Listowel [[Young Ireland]] Society<ref>Stenton & Lees (1978)</ref> and was a member of Kerry County Council and of the committee governing the County Infirmary, Tralee, the County Fever Hospital, Tralee and the County Mental Hospital, Killarney.  He married Mary Elizabeth Fitzgerald and they had three sons and two daughters.<ref>The Times, 7 December 1910; ''Who Was Who, 1941-1950''</ref>\n\nIn April 1896 he was returned unopposed as Anti-Parnellite Nationalist M.P. for North Kerry after the resignation of [[Thomas Sexton (Irish politician)|Thomas Sexton]].  Following the reunification of the Irish Parliamentary Party, he held the seat unopposed in 1900 and 1906.  In January 1910 he faced a challenge from an independent Nationalist, Thomas Stack, but was easily returned by 2,637 votes to 885. In December 1910 he was again returned unopposed.  He did not stand in the general election of 1918.<ref>Walker (1978)</ref>\n \nHe died at Tralee on 3 May 1944.<ref>The Times, 4 May 1944</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|title=Parliamentary Election Results in Ireland, 1801-1922|editor=Brian M. Walker|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|location=Dublin|year=1978}}\n*{{cite book|title=Who Was Who, 1941-1950|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=London|year=2012}}\n*{{cite book|title=Who\u2019s Who of British Members of Parliament, Vol.2 1886-1918|author=Michael Stenton and Stephen Lees|publisher=Harvester Press|location=Sussex|year=1978}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{hansard-contribs | mr-michael-flavin | Michael Flavin }}\n* {{cite TIWW |article= Flavin, Michael Joseph|page=84 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Stack (politician)|John Stack]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[North Kerry (UK Parliament constituency)|North Kerry]]\n | years = [[1896 North Kerry by-election|1896]] &ndash; [[1918 Irish general election|1918]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[James Crowley (Irish politician)|James Crowley]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flavin, Michael Joseph}}\n[[Category:1866 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Kerry constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:People from Listowel]]\n[[Category:People from Tralee]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in County Kerry]]\n[[Category:Anti-Parnellite MPs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1896-1918 \u2192 1896\u20131918", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Joseph_Flavin"}
{"title_page": "J. P. Farrell", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish Nationalist politician and newspaper founder}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:James Patrick Farrell.jpg|right|thumb|James Patrick Farrell, June 1899]]\n'''James Patrick Farrell''' (13 May 1865 \u2013 11 December 1921) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]] [[politician]] and [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) from 1895 to 1918, taking his seat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]].<ref name=\"rayment-hc-c3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Ccommons3.htm |title=Historical list of MPs: House of Commons constituencies beginning with \"C\", part 3 |work=Leigh Rayment's House of Commons pages |accessdate=2008-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829172904/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Ccommons3.htm |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"rayment-hc-l4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/lcommons4.htm |title=Historical list of MPs: House of Commons constituencies beginning with \"L\", part 4 |work=Leigh Rayment's House of Commons pages |accessdate=2008-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203104125/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Lcommons4.htm |archive-date=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was also founder (with fellow Nationalist M.P. [[Jasper Tully]]), owner and editor of the [[Longford Leader]] newspaper.<ref name=\"Profile_LongfdLdr_INA\">{{cite web |title=The Longford Leader |url=https://www.irishnewsarchive.com/longford-leader-newspaper-archive |website=Irish Newspaper Archives |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"leader\">{{cite news |title=St. Patrick's Day 1911 |url=http://www.longfordleader.ie/news/local-news/north-longford-1-1941338 |work=[[Longford Leader]] |date=16 March 2004 |accessdate=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111044926/http://www.longfordleader.ie/news/local-news/north-longford-1-1941338 |archive-date=11 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nFarrell was born in Longford on 13 May 1865, the son of Patrick Farrell of Longford, and Anne (n\u00e9e Lynam) of Strokestown, Co. Roscommon.  He attended St Mel's College, Longford.  In 1888, he married Bride Fitzgerald, and they had five sons and two daughters.<ref name=Thoms>{{cite wikisource|chapter=Farrell, James Patrick|wslink=Thom's Irish Who's Who|plaintitle=Thom's Irish Who's Who|last=|first=|year=1923|publisher=Alexander Thom & co.|page=76|wspage=|scan=|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Thom%27s_Irish_Who%27s_Who/Farrell,_James_Patrick|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>  \n\nAn active campaigner on land and tenancy reform, Farrell was arrested and imprisoned for two months in 1889 over a speech deemed to be agitation.<ref name=Thoms/> He stood as an [[Anti-Parnellite]] candidate at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|general election in July 1895]] in [[Kilkenny City (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilkenny City]], where the outgoing Anti-Parnellite MP [[Thomas Bartholomew Curran|Thomas Curran]] was not standing again. Farrell lost narrowly to the [[Parnellite]] candidate, [[Pat O'Brien (Irish politician)|Patrick O'Brien]] by a margin of only 667 votes to 681,<ref name=\"walker-1801-1922\">{{cite book\n | title  = Parliamentary election results in Ireland 1801\u20131922\n | editor = Brian M. Walker\n | publisher = Royal Irish Academy\n | location  = Dublin\n | year      = 1978\n | isbn      = 0-901714-12-7\n | page = 154\n}}</ref> but a vacancy arose immediately in [[West Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cavan]].  [[Edmund Vesey Knox]], who had been West Cavan's MP since 1890, was re-elected there in 1895 but also won a seat in [[Londonderry City (UK Parliament constituency)|Londonderry City]], and chose to sit for the latter.  The resulting by-election in West Cavan was held on 2 August 1895, and Farell was elected unopposed in the first by-election of that Parliament.<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 156</ref>\n\nFarrell was a fervent supporter of [[Land reforms by country#Ireland|land reform]] and spoke and wrote frequently on the subject. He was imprisoned four times between 1890 and 1910 and during his last imprisonment in [[Kilmainham Gaol]] contracted an illness which may have led to his death, aged 56, in 1921.<ref name=\"leader\"/>\n\nWhen the split in the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] was resolved in time for the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900 general election]], Farrell did not seek re-election in Cavan, but stood instead in [[North Longford (UK Parliament constituency)|North Longford]], where he was returned unopposed.<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 161</ref> He was re-elected unopposed in [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]], and at both elections in 1910,<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 363</ref> but at the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]] he was heavily defeated in the new [[Longford (UK Parliament constituency)|Longford constituency]] by the [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] candidate [[Joseph McGuinness]].<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 189</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-farrell | James Patrick Farrell }}\n* {{cite TIWW |article=Farrell, James Patrick |page=76 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[West Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cavan]]\n | years  = August 1895 \u2013 [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]]\n | before = [[Edmund Vesey Knox]]\n | after  = [[Thomas McGovern (politician)|Thomas McGovern]]\n}}\n\n{{s-bef | before = [[Justin McCarthy (historian and politician)|Justin McCarthy]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n |title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[North Longford (UK Parliament constituency)|North Longford]]\n |years  = [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900]] \u2013 [[1918 Irish general election|1918]]\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Farrell, J. P.}}\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:Irish Parliamentary Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Anti-Parnellite MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Cavan constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Longford constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1900\u20131906]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1906\u20131910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1910\u20131918]]\n[[Category:1921 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish Nationalist politician and newspaper founder}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:James Patrick Farrell.jpg|right|thumb|James Patrick Farrell, June 1899]]\n'''James Patrick Farrell''' (13 May 1865 \u2013 11 December 1921) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]] [[politician]] and [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) from 1895 to 1918, taking his seat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]].<ref name=\"rayment-hc-c3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Ccommons3.htm |title=Historical list of MPs: House of Commons constituencies beginning with \"C\", part 3 |work=Leigh Rayment's House of Commons pages |accessdate=2008-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829172904/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Ccommons3.htm |archive-date=29 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"rayment-hc-l4\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/lcommons4.htm |title=Historical list of MPs: House of Commons constituencies beginning with \"L\", part 4 |work=Leigh Rayment's House of Commons pages |accessdate=2008-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203104125/http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Lcommons4.htm |archive-date=3 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was also founder (with fellow Nationalist M.P. [[Jasper Tully]]), owner and editor of the [[Longford Leader]] newspaper.<ref name=\"Profile_LongfdLdr_INA\">{{cite web |title=The Longford Leader |url=https://www.irishnewsarchive.com/longford-leader-newspaper-archive |website=Irish Newspaper Archives |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"leader\">{{cite news |title=St. Patrick's Day 1911 |url=http://www.longfordleader.ie/news/local-news/north-longford-1-1941338 |work=[[Longford Leader]] |date=16 March 2004 |accessdate=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111044926/http://www.longfordleader.ie/news/local-news/north-longford-1-1941338 |archive-date=11 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nFarrell was born in Longford on 13 May 1865, the son of Patrick Farrell of Longford, and Anne (ne\u00e9 Lynam) of Strokestown, Co. Roscommon.  He attended St Mel's College, Longford.  In 1888, he married Bride Fitzgerald, and they had five sons and two daughters.<ref name=Thoms>{{cite wikisource|chapter=Farrell, James Patrick|wslink=Thom's Irish Who's Who|plaintitle=Thom's Irish Who's Who|last=|first=|year=1923|publisher=Alexander Thom & co.|page=76|wspage=|scan=|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Thom%27s_Irish_Who%27s_Who/Farrell,_James_Patrick|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>  \n\nAn active campaigner on land and tenancy reform, Farrell was arrested and imprisoned for two months in 1889 over a speech deemed to be agitation.<ref name=Thoms/> He stood as an [[Anti-Parnellite]] candidate at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|general election in July 1895]] in [[Kilkenny City (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilkenny City]], where the outgoing Anti-Parnellite MP [[Thomas Bartholomew Curran|Thomas Curran]] was not standing again. Farrell lost narrowly to the [[Parnellite]] candidate, [[Pat O'Brien (Irish politician)|Patrick O'Brien]] by a margin of only 667 votes to 681,<ref name=\"walker-1801-1922\">{{cite book\n | title  = Parliamentary election results in Ireland 1801\u20131922\n | editor = Brian M. Walker\n | publisher = Royal Irish Academy\n | location  = Dublin\n | year      = 1978\n | isbn      = 0-901714-12-7\n | page = 154\n}}</ref> but a vacancy arose immediately in [[West Cavan (UK Parliament constituency)|West Cavan]].  [[Edmund Vesey Knox]], who had been West Cavan's MP since 1890, was re-elected there in 1895 but also won a seat in [[Londonderry City (UK Parliament constituency)|Londonderry City]], and chose to sit for the latter.  The resulting by-election in West Cavan was held on 2 August 1895, and Farell was elected unopposed in the first by-election of that Parliament.<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 156</ref>\n\nFarrell was a fervent supporter of [[Land reforms by country#Ireland|land reform]] and spoke and wrote frequently on the subject. He was imprisoned four times between 1890 and 1910 and during his last imprisonment in [[Kilmainham Gaol]] contracted an illness which may have led to his death, aged 56, in 1921.<ref name=\"leader\"/>\n\nWhen the split in the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] was resolved in time for the [[1900 United Kingdom general election|1900 general election]], Farrell did not seek re-election in Cavan, but stood instead in [[North Longford (UK Parliament constituency)|North Longford]], where he was returned unopposed.<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 161</ref> He was re-elected unopposed in [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]], and at both elections in 1910,<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 363</ref> but at the [[1918 Irish general election|1918 general election]] he was heavily defeated in the new [[Longford (UK Parliament constituency)|Longford constituency]] by the [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] candidate [[Joseph McGuinness]].<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 189</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-james-farrell | James Patrick Farrell }}\n* {{cite TIWW |