{"title_page": "Tiara Andini (singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Indonesian singer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Tiara Andini\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Tiara Anugrah Eka Setyo Andini\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|2001|09|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Jember]], Indonesia\n| occupation = {{flat list|\n* Singer\n}}\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{flat list|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]}}\n| instrument = {{flat list|\n* Vocals\n}}\n| years_active = 2018\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Universal Music Group]]\n}}\n| associated_acts =\n\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Tiara Anugrah Eka Setyo Andini''' (born 23 September 2001) or introduced by the stage name '''Tiara Andini''' is an [[Indonesia]]n singer. She is known as runner up [[Indonesian_Idol_(season_10)|the tenth season]] of [[Indonesian Idol]], broadcast by the national television channels [[RCTI]] in 2019-2020.<ref>[https://www.tribunnews.com/nasional/2020/01/28/indonesian-idol-tiara-anugrah-raih-5-standing-ovation-dari-juri-judika-kagum-dengan-penampilannya Indonesian Idol: Tiara Anugrah Raih 5 Standing Ovation dari Juri, Judika Kagum dengan Penampilannya] Tribunnews.com (in Indonesian). Retrieved 28 January 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.inews.id/lifestyle/music/tiara-raih-5-standing-ovation-anang-hermansyah-hari-ini-lahir-superstar Tiara Raih 5 Standing Ovation, Anang Hermansyah: Hari Ini Lahir Superstar] inews.id.(in Indonesian) Retrieved 28 January 2020.</ref><ref>[https://celebrity.okezone.com/read/2020/01/28/598/2159551/dapat-5-standing-ovation-di-indonesian-idol-anang-sebut-tiara-superstar Dapat 5 Standing Ovation di Indonesian Idol, Anang Sebut Tiara Superstar] okezone.com.(in Indonesian) Retrieved 28 January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Life and Career ==\nIn 2018, Tiara was entrusted to be the prototype fashion show of [[Jember Fashion Carnaval]] with the theme of [[South Korea]] at the close of the 2018 [[Asian Games]]. At that time, Tiara also had the opportunity to get a moment with one of the famous boy groups from South Korea, [[Super Junior]].\n\n== Performances on [[Indonesian_Idol_(season_10)|Indonesian Idol X]] ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Theme\n! scope=\"col\" |Song\n! scope=\"col\" |Original Singer\n! scope=\"col\" |result\n|-\n|Audition\n|\"Could it Be\"\n|[[Raisa (singer)|Raisa]]\n|Titanium Ticket\n(from Judika)\n|-\n|Elimination 1 : Acapella\n|\"Reflection\" \n|[[Christina Aguilera]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Elimination 2 : Grup : Best of the Best\n| \"If I Ain't You\"\n|[[Alicia Keys]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Elimination 3 : Solo\n|\"Karena Ku Sanggup\"\n|[[Agnez Mo]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Showcase 1\n|\"New York, New York\"\n|[[Frank Sinatra]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Final Showcase 1\n|\"Cinta Luar Biasa\"\n|Andmesh\n|Judges choice, Saved by Judika\n|-\n|Specta 1\n|\"Lily\"\n|[[K-391]], [[Alan Walker (music producer)|Alan Walker]], Emelie Hollow\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 2\n|\"So Am I\"\n|[[Ava Max]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 3\n|\"One Moment in Time\"\n|[[Whitney Houston]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 4\n|\"Happier\"\n|[[Ed Sheeran]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 5\n|\"Untuk Apa\"\n|[[Maudy Ayunda]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 6\n|\"Kiss and Make Up\"\n|[[Dua Lipa]] & [[Blackpink]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 7\n|\"Dia\"\n|[[Vina Panduwinata]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 8\n|\"Pamer Bojo\"\n|Didi Kempot\n|Bottom 3\n|-\n|Specta 9\n|\"Sedih Tak Berujung\"\n|[[Glenn Fredly]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 10\n|\"Waktu yang Salah\"\n|Fiersa Besari & Thantri\n|Safe\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Specta 11\n|\"Like I'm Gonna Lose You\"\n|[[Meghan Trainor]] & [[John Legend]]\n|rowspan ='2'|Safe\n|-\n|\"Miliki Aku\"\n|Dea Mirella\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Specta 12\n|\"Surat Cinta untuk Starla\"\n|Virgoun\n|rowspan ='2'|Safe\n|-\n|\"Flashlight\"\n|[[Jessie J]]\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Road to Grand Final\n|\"Cinta Sendiri\"\n|[[Kahitna]]\n|rowspan ='2'|Safe\n|-\n|\"Bahasa Kalbu\"\n|[[Titi DJ]]\n|-\n|rowspan ='4'|Grand Final\n|\"Kertonyono Medot Janji\"\n|Denny Caknan\n|rowspan ='6'|Runner up\n|-\n|\"Kangen\"\n|[[Dewa 19]]\n|-\n|\"The Greatest Love of All\"\n|[[Whitney Houston]]\n|-\n|\"Gemintang Hatiku\"\n|Tiara Andini\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Result & Reunion\n|\"Pamer Bojo\"\n|Didi Kempot\n|-\n|\"I Surrender\"\n|[[Celine Dion]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n===Single===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Song\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Chart\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard Indonesia Top 100|IDN]]<br /><ref name=\"IDNsingles\">{{cite web |url=https://billboardid.com/top100/ |title=Billboard Indonesia Top 100 |work=billboardid.com |publisher=Billboard Indonesia |accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Gemintang Hatiku\"\n| 2020\n| 16\n| {{n/a|Singel non-album}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{instagram|tiaraanugrahh}}\n* {{twitter|tiaraIdol10}}\n* {{facebook|TiaraIdol10}}\n* {{YouTube|channel=UC6B6N7-2yNGDZtLhAeTj6mA|Tiara Andini}}\n\n{{Indonesian Idol}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Indonesian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian child singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian female singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from East Java]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indonesian singer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Tiara Andini\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Tiara Anugrah Eka Setyo Andini\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|2001|09|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Jember]], Indonesia\n| occupation = {{flat list|\n* Singer\n}}\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{flat list|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]}}\n| instrument = {{flat list|\n* Vocals\n}}\n| years_active = 2018\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Universal Music Group]]\n}}\n| associated_acts =\n\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Tiara Anugrah Eka Setyo Andini''' (born 23 September 2001) or introduced by the stage name '''Tiara Andini''' is an [[Indonesia]]n singer. She is known as runner up [[Indonesian_Idol_(season_10)|the tenth season]] of [[Indonesian Idol]], broadcast by the national television channels [[RCTI]] in 2019-2020.<ref>[https://www.tribunnews.com/nasional/2020/01/28/indonesian-idol-tiara-anugrah-raih-5-standing-ovation-dari-juri-judika-kagum-dengan-penampilannya Indonesian Idol: Tiara Anugrah Raih 5 Standing Ovation dari Juri, Judika Kagum dengan Penampilannya] Tribunnews.com (in Indonesian). Retrieved 28 January 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.inews.id/lifestyle/music/tiara-raih-5-standing-ovation-anang-hermansyah-hari-ini-lahir-superstar Tiara Raih 5 Standing Ovation, Anang Hermansyah: Hari Ini Lahir Superstar] inews.id.(in Indonesian) Retrieved 28 January 2020.</ref><ref>[https://celebrity.okezone.com/read/2020/01/28/598/2159551/dapat-5-standing-ovation-di-indonesian-idol-anang-sebut-tiara-superstar Dapat 5 Standing Ovation di Indonesian Idol, Anang Sebut Tiara Superstar] okezone.com.(in Indonesian) Retrieved 28 January 2020.</ref>\n\n== Life and Career ==\nIn 2018, Tiara was entrusted to be the prototype fashion show of [[Jember Fashion Carnaval]] with the theme of [[South Korea]] at the close of the 2018 [[Asian Games]]. At that time, Tiara also had the opportunity to get a moment with one of the famous boy groups from South Korea, [[Super Junior]].\n\n== Performances on [[Indonesian_Idol_(season_10)|Indonesian Idol X]] ==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Theme\n! scope=\"col\" |Song\n! scope=\"col\" |Original Singer\n! scope=\"col\" |result\n|-\n|Audition\n|\"Could it Be\"\n|[[Raisa]]\n|Titanium Ticket\n(from Judika)\n|-\n|Elimination 1 : Acapella\n|\"Reflection\" \n|[[Christina Aguilera]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Elimination 2 : Grup : Best of the Best\n| \"If I Ain't You\"\n|[[Alicia Keys]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Elimination 3 : Solo\n|\"Karena Ku Sanggup\"\n|[[Agnez Mo]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Showcase 1\n|\"New York, New York\"\n|[[Frank Sinatra]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Final Showcase 1\n|\"Cinta Luar Biasa\"\n|Andmesh\n|Judges choice, Saved by Judika\n|-\n|Specta 1\n|\"Lily\"\n|[[K-391]], [[Alan Walker]], Emelie Hollow\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 2\n|\"So Am I\"\n|[[Ava Max]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 3\n|\"One Moment in Time\"\n|[[Whitney Houston]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 4\n|\"Happier\"\n|[[Ed Sheeran]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 5\n|\"Untuk Apa\"\n|[[Maudy Ayunda]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 6\n|\"Kiss and Make Up\"\n|[[Dua Lipa]] & [[Blackpink]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 7\n|\"Dia\"\n|[[Vina Panduwinata]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 8\n|\"Pamer Bojo\"\n|Didi Kempot\n|Bottom 3\n|-\n|Specta 9\n|\"Sedih Tak Berujung\"\n|[[Glenn Fredly]]\n|Safe\n|-\n|Specta 10\n|\"Waktu yang Salah\"\n|Fiersa Besari & Thantri\n|Safe\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Specta 11\n|\"Like I'm Gonna Lose You\"\n|[[Meghan Trainor]] & [[John Legend]]\n|rowspan ='2'|Safe\n|-\n|\"Miliki Aku\"\n|Dea Mirella\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Specta 12\n|\"Surat Cinta untuk Starla\"\n|Virgoun\n|rowspan ='2'|Safe\n|-\n|\"Flashlight\"\n|[[Jessie J]]\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Road to Grand Final\n|\"Cinta Sendiri\"\n|[[Kahitna]]\n|rowspan ='2'|Safe\n|-\n|\"Bahasa Kalbu\"\n|[[Titi DJ]]\n|-\n|rowspan ='4'|Grand Final\n|\"Kertonyono Medot Janji\"\n|Denny Caknan\n|rowspan ='6'|Runner up\n|-\n|\"Kangen\"\n|[[Dewa 19]]\n|-\n|\"The Greatest Love of All\"\n|[[Whitney Houston]]\n|-\n|\"Gemintang Hatiku\"\n|Tiara Andini\n|-\n|rowspan ='2'|Result & Reunion\n|\"Pamer Bojo\"\n|Didi Kempot\n|-\n|\"I Surrender\"\n|[[Celine Dion]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n===Single===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Song\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Chart\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard Indonesia Top 100|IDN]]<br /><ref name=\"IDNsingles\">{{cite web |url=https://billboardid.com/top100/ |title=Billboard Indonesia Top 100 |work=billboardid.com |publisher=Billboard Indonesia |accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Gemintang Hatiku\"\n| 2020\n| 16\n| {{n/a|Singel non-album}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{instagram|tiaraanugrahh}}\n* {{twitter|tiaraIdol10}}\n* {{facebook|TiaraIdol10}}\n* {{YouTube|channel=UC6B6N7-2yNGDZtLhAeTj6mA|Tiara Andini}}\n\n{{Indonesian Idol}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:Indonesian-language singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian child singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian female singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian singers]]\n[[Category:Indonesian pop singers]]\n[[Category:People from East Java]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Raisa\u2192Raisa (singer),Alan Walker\u2192Alan Walker (music producer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiara_Andini_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "John Daly (Fenian)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name =John Daly<br>{{lang|ga|Se\u00e1n \u00d3 D\u00e1laigh}}\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|df=yes|1845|10|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Limerick City]], [[County Limerick]], Ireland\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1916|6|30|1845|10|18|df=y}}\n|death_place  = Ireland\n|image        = John Daly (Fenian).JPG\n|other_names  = \n|spouse       =\n|children     = \n|relatives    = [[Ned Daly]]<br>[[Kathleen Clarke]]\n|movement     = [[Irish republicanism]]\n|organization = [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]]<Br>[[Irish National League]]\n|monuments =\n|alma_mater =\n|awards =\n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Daly''' (18 October 1845 \u2013 30 June 1916), was an Irish revolutionary, and a leading member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]]. He was uncle to [[Kathleen Clarke]], wife of [[Tom Clarke (Irish republican)|Tom Clarke]], executed for his part in the [[Easter Rising|1916 Rising]] who was a leading member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood|IRB]], and her brother [[Ned Daly]] who was also executed in 1916.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Daly was born in [[Limerick]] city on 18 October 1845. His father worked in James Harvey & Son's Timber Yard. At 16 John joined his father working as a [[lath]] splitter. At 18 he was sworn in as a member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]], also known as the Fenians, and became fully involved in Republican activities. When he was refused absolution in confession because he admitted to being a Fenian, he decided that from then on his loyalty would no longer be to \"faith and Fatherland\" but to \"God and Fatherland.\"<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 2\">Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 2</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 1866 Daly and his brother Edward were arrested at their family home having been betrayed by an informer, for running a munitions factory in the Pennywell district close to their home. He was released on bail in February 1867 toughened and more dedicated by the experience.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 2\"/>\n\n==1867 Rising==\nOn 5 March 1867 the ill-prepared [[Fenian Rising]] took place. John Daly took charge of the Limerick detachment of the IRB. Limerick was one of the few areas were the Fenians were able to make some show of force, however weak. Through lack of numbers they failed to make a significant impact on the vastly superior forces arrayed against them. Moving out of the city, Daly moved his men into the country and joined up with other Fenians in an attack on the [[Irish Constabulary]] barracks at [[Kilmallock]]. The attack was repelled and Daly dispersed his men.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\">Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3</ref>\n\nAfter this Daly had to flee the country by stowing away first on a boat the ''Hollywood'', to England, and from London then on board the ''Cornelius Grenfel'' to the United States of America.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\"/><ref>D. J. Hickey & J. E. Doherty pg. 104</ref>\n\n==America==\nLife in America for working class immigrants was particularly tough and his first job on leaving the ship was digging a cellar. He then obtained work in a white lead factory and worked for a while as a mason's help before getting a reasonably good job as a brakeman on a tram system. Daly was to recall these experiences in his ''Recollections of Fenians and Fenianism''.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\"/>\n\n==Amnesty Association==\nIn 1869 Daly returned to Ireland and took up his old job in the timber yard, and also his Republican activities. He began to help reorganise the IRB and took part in a number of agitations to keep the IRB agenda in the public view. He became a leading voice in the [[Amnesty Association]] to help in the release of those Fenians still in jail.<ref>Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\u20134</ref><ref>Owen McGee, pg. 41\u201342</ref>\n\nIn November 1869 a major tenants' right meeting took place in the city. The IRB objected to the meeting because the issue of the prisoners was not on the agenda.  In what came to be known as \"The Battle of the Markets\" the IRB charged the platform and succeeded in dismantling it. Though the organisers of the meeting attempted to hold some form of gathering, Daly and the IRB refused to relent. It was Daly's opinion that \"it was one of the greatest moral victories ever achieved\". The issue of the political prisoners was to keep Daly occupied for much of the 1870s. In 1876 Daly was again arrested for disturbing another home rule gathering, though on being brought before the court he was acquitted.<ref>Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 4</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Land War]] Daly was a member of the Supreme Council of the IRB and became organiser for Connacht and Ulster.\n\n==Arrest==\nIn the summer of 1883, Daly moved to [[Birmingham]], England, and settled in the home of [[James Egan (Fenian)|James Egan]], an old friend from Limerick and a generally inactive IRB man. E.G. Jenkinson, head of Special Branch, was informed that John Daly was on his way to Britain from America; Daly had been asked by the Supreme Council to deliver the graveside oration at the funeral of [[Charles Kickham|Charles J. Kickham]] while in the United States. When Daly arrived, a plain-clothes detective was assigned to follow him at all times. As a result of this, Special Branch were alerted to the importance of [[John Torley]] in Glasgow, Robert Johnston<ref>Robert Johnston was the father of [[Ethna Carbery]] Irish writer and poet (''cite'', M. Ryan, pg.64)</ref> in Belfast and [[Mark F. Ryan|Mark Ryan]] in London of the IRB.<ref>Owen McGee, pg. 119</ref>\n\nJenkinson used [[Agent provocateur|agents provocateurs]] in his attempts to convict Republicans. One such recruit was a publican and local IRB man named Dan O'Neill. Both Jenkinson and a Major [[Nicholas Gosselin]] persuaded O'Neill to betray Daly. O'Neill then ask Daly to deliver sealed cases to some associates in London, and on 11 April Daly was arrested as he was about to board the train for London, and explosives were found in the case he was carrying. The police then raided the home of James Egan where explosives were \"allegedly found buried\" in Egan's garden in addition to some documents.<ref>Owen McGee, pg. 121</ref>\n\nIn Chatham prison he became friends with [[Tom Clarke (Irish republican)|Tom Clarke]], who would later marry his niece [[Kathleen Clarke|Kathleen]] and who was a leader of the 1916 [[Easter Rising]]. While in prison he claimed that he was being poisoned with [[Atropa belladonna|belladonna]] which caused an investigation by a commission of inquiry, 1890; it was admitted by prison officials as an error by a warder.<ref>Commons Papers index. Chatham Prison (Treatment of Felony Prisoners), Report of the Visitors, ...1890, p.xxx, vii, 629. See also ''That Irishman'', Jane Stanford, 2011, pps 180,181.</ref> A series of articles in the ''Daily Chronicle'' in 1894 analysed prison methods. Daly gave an interview to the ''Chronicle'' which appeared 12 September 1896.\n\nThe head of the Birmingham police later made a deathbed confession that Daly had been \"convicted on perjured evidence\".\n\n==Released==\nDaly was unopposed elected as a member of parliament (MP) for [[Limerick City (UK Parliament constituency)|Limerick City]] at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|general election in July 1895]], as a member of the [[Charles Stewart Parnell|Parnellite]] [[Irish National League]].  However, he was disqualified on 19 August 1895 as a treason-felon.<ref name=\"walker-1801-1922\">{{cite book\n | title  = Parliamentary election results in Ireland 1801\u20131922\n | editor = Brian M. Walker\n | publisher = Royal Irish Academy\n | location  = Dublin\n | year      = 1978\n | isbn      = 0-901714-12-7\n | page = 154\n}}</ref> In August 1896, he went on a lecture tour of England with [[Maud Gonne]] and in 1897 on a tour of American which was organised by John Devoy. He later founded a prosperous bakery business in Limerick, and went on to become Mayor of his native city.\n\n==Mayor of Limerick==\nJohn Daly was elected three times as [[Mayor of Limerick]] City, from 1899\u20131901. He jointly financed with [[Patrick McCartan]] the IRB newspaper ''[[Irish Freedom]]'' in 1910.\n\n==The Daly Cup==\nIn 1928, Madge Daly, a niece of John Daly, presented the Daly cup to William P. Clifford, the then-chairman of the [[Limerick GAA]] county board.<ref>{{cite web|last=Greensmyth|first=Harry|title=Who is the Daly Cup named after?|url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/sport/who_is_the_daly_cup_named_after_by_harry_greensmyth_1_2177345|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804092426/http://www.limerickleader.ie/sport/who_is_the_daly_cup_named_after_by_harry_greensmyth_1_2177345|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-08-04|work=Who is the Daly Cup named after?|publisher=Limerick Leader}}</ref> Since then, the Daly cup is presented to the winners of the [[Limerick Senior Hurling Championship]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n* D.J. Hickey & J.E. Doherty (2003), ''A new Dictionary of Irish History from 1800'', Gill & Macmillan, {{ISBN|0-7171-2520-3}}\n* Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa, ''John Daly, The Fenian Mayor of Limerick''\n* Owen McGee (2005), ''The IRB: The Irish Republican Brotherhood from The Land League to Sinn F\u00e9in'', Four Courts Press, {{ISBN|1-85182-972-5}}\n*''Fenian Memories'', Dr. Mark F. Ryan, M. H. Gill & Son, Ltd, Dublin, 1945\n*''Irish Political Prisoners,1848-1922, Theatres of War'', Sean McConville, 2003, pps, 365, 377.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-daly-1 | John Daly }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071122102144/http://askaboutireland.ie/show_narrative_page.do?page_id=3368 Ask About Ireland]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080505165307/http://www.limerick.com/lifestyle/bishop_odwyer.html \"Bishop Edward Thomas O Dwyer of Limerick 1842 \u2013 1917\"]\n*[http://limerick1916.ul.ie/ Limerick and the 1916 Rising]. A digital exhibition based on the Daly collection at the Glucksman Library, University of Limerick.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before  = [[Francis Arthur O'Keefe]] }}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Limerick City (UK Parliament constituency)|Limerick City]]\n | years = [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] \u2013 [[1895 Limerick City by-election|1895]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Francis Arthur O'Keefe]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{\u00d3 D\u00e1laigh}}\n{{IRB}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daly, John}}\n[[Category:People of the Fenian dynamite campaign]]\n[[Category:People of the Fenian Rising]]\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Irish Republican Brotherhood]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Limerick (city)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1895\u20131900]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for County Limerick constituencies (1801\u20131922)]]\n[[Category:National League Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Parnellite MPs]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name =John Daly<br>{{lang|ga|Se\u00e1n \u00d3 D\u00e1laigh}}\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|df=yes|1845|10|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Limerick City]], [[County Limerick]], Ireland\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1916|6|30|1845|10|18|df=y}}\n|death_place  = Ireland\n|image        = John Daly (Fenian).JPG\n|other_names  = \n|spouse       =\n|children     = \n|relatives    = [[Ned Daly]]<br>[[Kathleen Clarke]]\n|movement     = [[Irish republicanism]]\n|organization = [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]]<Br>[[Irish National League]]\n|monuments =\n|alma_mater =\n|awards =\n|footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Daly''' (18 October 1845 \u2013 30 June 1916), was an Irish revolutionary, and a leading member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]]. He was uncle to [[Kathleen Clarke]], wife of [[Tom Clarke (Irish republican)|Tom Clarke]], executed for his part in the [[Easter Rising|1916 Rising]] who was a leading member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood|IRB]], and her brother [[Ned Daly]] who was also executed in 1916.\n\n==Early life==\nJohn Daly was born in [[Limerick]] city on 18 October 1845. His father worked in James Harvey & Son's Timber Yard. At 16 John joined his father working as a [[lath]] splitter. At 18 he was sworn in as a member of the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood]], also known as the Fenians, and became fully involved in Republican activities. When he was refused absolution in confession because he admitted to being a Fenian, he decided that from then on his loyalty would no longer be to \"faith and Fatherland\" but to \"God and Fatherland.\"<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 2\">Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 2</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 1866 Daly and his brother Edward were arrested at their family home having been betrayed by an informer, for running a munitions factory in the Pennywell district close to their home. He was released on bail in February 1867 toughened and more dedicated by the experience.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 2\"/>\n\n==1867 Rising==\nOn 5 March 1867 the ill-prepared [[Fenian Rising]] took place. John Daly took charge of the Limerick detachment of the IRB. Limerick was one of the few areas were the Fenians were able to make some show of force, however weak. Through lack of numbers they failed to make a significant impact on the vastly superior forces arrayed against them. Moving out of the city, Daly moved his men into the country and joined up with other Fenians in an attack on the [[Irish Constabulary]] barracks at [[Kilmallock]]. The attack was repelled and Daly dispersed his men.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\">Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3</ref>\n\nAfter this Daly had to flee the country by stowing away first on a boat the ''Hollywood'', to England, and from London then on board the ''Cornelius Grenfel'' to the United States of America.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\"/><ref>D. J. Hickey & J. E. Doherty pg. 104</ref>\n\n==America==\nLife in America for working class immigrants was particularly tough and his first job on leaving the ship was digging a cellar. He then obtained work in a white lead factory and worked for a while as a mason's help before getting a reasonably good job as a brakeman on a tram system. Daly was to recall these experiences in his ''Recollections of Fenians and Fenianism''.<ref name=\"Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\"/>\n\n==Amnesty Association==\nIn 1869 Daly returned to Ireland and took up his old job in the timber yard, and also his Republican activities. He began to help reorganise the IRB and took part in a number of agitations to keep the IRB agenda in the public view. He became a leading voice in the [[Amnesty Association]] to help in the release of those Fenians still in jail.<ref>Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 3\u20134</ref><ref>Owen McGee, pg. 41\u201342</ref>\n\nIn November 1869 a major tenants' right meeting took place in the city. The IRB objected to the meeting because the issue of the prisoners was not on the agenda.  In what came to be known as \"The Battle of the Markets\" the IRB charged the platform and succeeded in dismantling it. Though the organisers of the meeting attempted to hold some form of gathering, Daly and the IRB refused to relent. It was Daly's opinion that \"it was one of the greatest moral victories ever achieved\". The issue of the political prisoners was to keep Daly occupied for much of the 1870s. In 1876 Daly was again arrested for disturbing another home rule gathering, though on being brought before the court he was acquitted.<ref>Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa pg. 4</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Land War]] Daly was a member of the Supreme Council of the IRB and became organiser for Connacht and Ulster.\n\n==Arrest==\nIn the summer of 1883, Daly moved to [[Birmingham]], England, and settled in the home of [[James Egan (Fenian)|James Egan]], an old friend from Limerick and a generally inactive IRB man. E.G. Jenkinson, head of Special Branch, was informed that John Daly was on his way to Britain from America; Daly had been asked by the Supreme Council to deliver the graveside oration at the funeral of [[Charles Kickham|Charles J. Kickham]] while in the United States. When Daly arrived, a plain-clothes detective was assigned to follow him at all times. As a result of this, Special Branch were alerted to the importance of [[John Torley]] in Glasgow, Robert Johnston<ref>Robert Johnston was the father of [[Ethna Carbery]] Irish writer and poet (''cite'', M. Ryan, pg.64)</ref> in Belfast and [[Mark F. Ryan|Mark Ryan]] in London of the IRB.<ref>Owen McGee, pg. 119</ref>\n\nJenkinson used [[Agent provocateur|agents provocateurs]] in his attempts to convict Republicans. One such recruit was a publican and local IRB man named Dan O'Neill. Both Jenkinson and a Major [[Nicholas Gosselin]] persuaded O'Neill to betray Daly. O'Neill then ask Daly to deliver sealed cases to some associates in London, and on 11 April Daly was arrested as he was about to board the train for London, and explosives were found in the case he was carrying. The police then raided the home of James Egan where explosives were \"allegedly found buried\" in Egan's garden in addition to some documents.<ref>Owen McGee, pg. 121</ref>\n\nIn Chatham prison he became friends with [[Tom Clarke (Irish republican)|Tom Clarke]], who would later marry his niece [[Kathleen Clarke|Kathleen]] and who was a leader of the 1916 [[Easter Rising]]. While in prison he claimed that he was being poisoned with [[Atropa belladonna|belladonna]] which caused an investigation by a commission of inquiry, 1890; it was admitted by prison officials as an error by a warder.<ref>Commons Papers index. Chatham Prison (Treatment of Felony Prisoners), Report of the Visitors, ...1890, p.xxx, vii, 629. See also ''That Irishman'', Jane Stanford, 2011, pps 180,181.</ref> A series of articles in the ''Daily Chronicle'' in 1894 analysed prison methods. Daly gave an interview to the ''Chronicle'' which appeared 12 September 1896.\n\nThe head of the Birmingham police later made a deathbed confession that Daly had been \"convicted on perjured evidence\".\n\n==Released==\nDaly was unopposed elected as a member of parliament (MP) for [[Limerick City (UK Parliament constituency)|Limerick City]] at the [[1895 United Kingdom general election|general election in July 1895]], as a member of the [[Charles Stewart Parnell|Parnellite]] [[Irish National League]].  However, he was disqualified on 19 August 1895 as a treason-felon.<ref name=\"walker-1801-1922\">{{cite book\n | title  = Parliamentary election results in Ireland 1801\u20131922\n | editor = Brian M. Walker\n | publisher = Royal Irish Academy\n | location  = Dublin\n | year      = 1978\n | isbn      = 0-901714-12-7\n | page = 154\n}}</ref> In August 1896, he went on a lecture tour of England with [[Maud Gonne]] and in 1897 on a tour of American which was organised by John Devoy. He later founded a prosperous bakery business in Limerick, and went on to become Mayor of his native city.\n\n==Mayor of Limerick==\nJohn Daly was elected three times as [[Mayor of Limerick]] City, from 1899\u20141901. He jointly financed with [[Patrick McCartan]] the IRB newspaper ''[[Irish Freedom]]'' in 1910.\n\n==The Daly Cup==\nIn 1928, Madge Daly, a niece of John Daly, presented the Daly cup to William P. Clifford, the then-chairman of the [[Limerick GAA]] county board.<ref>{{cite web|last=Greensmyth|first=Harry|title=Who is the Daly Cup named after?|url=http://www.limerickleader.ie/sport/who_is_the_daly_cup_named_after_by_harry_greensmyth_1_2177345|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804092426/http://www.limerickleader.ie/sport/who_is_the_daly_cup_named_after_by_harry_greensmyth_1_2177345|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-08-04|work=Who is the Daly Cup named after?|publisher=Limerick Leader}}</ref> Since then, the Daly cup is presented to the winners of the [[Limerick Senior Hurling Championship]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n* D.J. Hickey & J.E. Doherty (2003), ''A new Dictionary of Irish History from 1800'', Gill & Macmillan, {{ISBN|0-7171-2520-3}}\n* Ciar\u00e1n \u00d3 Gr\u00edofa, ''John Daly, The Fenian Mayor of Limerick''\n* Owen McGee (2005), ''The IRB: The Irish Republican Brotherhood from The Land League to Sinn F\u00e9in'', Four Courts Press, {{ISBN|1-85182-972-5}}\n*''Fenian Memories'', Dr. Mark F. Ryan, M. H. Gill & Son, Ltd, Dublin, 1945\n*''Irish Political Prisoners,1848-1922, Theatres of War'', Sean McConville, 2003, pps, 365, 377.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-john-daly-1 | John Daly }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071122102144/http://askaboutireland.ie/show_narrative_page.do?page_id=3368 Ask About Ireland]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080505165307/http://www.limerick.com/lifestyle/bishop_odwyer.html \"Bishop Edward Thomas O Dwyer of Limerick 1842 \u2013 1917\"]\n*[http://limerick1916.ul.ie/ Limerick and the 1916 Rising]. A digital exhibition based on the Daly collection at the Glucksman Library, University of Limerick.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before  = [[Francis Arthur O'Keefe]] }}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Limerick City (UK Parliament constituency)|Limerick City]]\n | years = [[1895 United Kingdom general election|1895]] \u2013 [[1895 Limerick City by-election|1895]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Francis Arthur O'Keefe]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{\u00d3 D\u00e1laigh}}\n{{IRB}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daly, John}}\n[[Category:People of the Fenian dynamite campaign]]\n[[Category:People of the Fenian Rising]]\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\